<fig id="fig03" fig-type="figure" orientation="portrait" position="float">
 <label>Fig. 3.</label>
 <caption>
  <p>(
   <italic>A</italic> and 
   <italic>B</italic>) Two types of 1D bismuth rods that preserve the twofold rotation symmetry 
   <inline-formula>
    <math id="i155">
     <msub>
      <mrow>
       <mn>2</mn>
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mo>[</mo>
        <mrow>
         <mn>1</mn>
         <mrow>
          <mover accent="true">
           <mrow>
            <mn>1</mn>
           </mrow>
           <mo>¯</mo>
          </mover>
         </mrow>
         <mn>0</mn>
        </mrow>
        <mo>]</mo>
       </mrow>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </math>
   </inline-formula>. These rods are periodic along the 
   <inline-formula>
    <math id="i156">
     <mrow>
      <mo>[</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mn>1</mn>
       <mrow>
        <mover accent="true">
         <mrow>
          <mn>1</mn>
         </mrow>
         <mo>¯</mo>
        </mover>
       </mrow>
       <mn>0</mn>
      </mrow>
      <mo>]</mo>
     </mrow>
    </math>
   </inline-formula> axis but finite sized within the plane that is perpendicular to 
   <inline-formula>
    <math id="i157">
     <mrow>
      <mo>[</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mn>1</mn>
       <mrow>
        <mover accent="true">
         <mrow>
          <mn>1</mn>
         </mrow>
         <mo>¯</mo>
        </mover>
       </mrow>
       <mn>0</mn>
      </mrow>
      <mo>]</mo>
     </mrow>
    </math>
   </inline-formula>. In the first rod (
   <italic>A</italic>), the side surfaces are the (111) and 
   <inline-formula>
    <math id="i158">
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mn>11</mn>
       <mrow>
        <mover accent="true">
         <mrow>
          <mn>2</mn>
         </mrow>
         <mo>¯</mo>
        </mover>
       </mrow>
      </mrow>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </math>
   </inline-formula> surfaces and the cross-section is a rectangle. (
   <italic>C</italic> and 
   <italic>D</italic>) Energy dispersions of rods 1 and 2. The topological hinge states are marked by red lines. (
   <italic>E</italic> and 
   <italic>F</italic>) Real-space distributions of the hinge states of rods 1 and 2.
  </p>
 </caption>
